This group is here just to give you a way to plug in a pre-existing workflow (like, generating a photo, using controlnet over an existing picture to generate a new one, etc.).

It's turned off by default, since this is a relight-only workflow, but you can use this as the endpoint of any workflow where you need to relight people (and most probably products too).

This is a workflow aimed at relighting people, while preserving details and colors as much as possible.

The main issues when both preserving details and color, is that the frequency separation technique has its limitations, be it either here in comfyUI (more limitations) or in Photoshop (less limitations). 

The main limitation is that we're working in 8bit space, which is terrible for remapping radically different histograms when color matching.

Also, the high frequency layer that holds the details still keeps a bit of the original lighting infos, so there's only so much you can do about that.

My main suggestions here would be:
- keep a very low CFG (1.1-1.5) in the relighting KSampler, to avoid changing the original picture drastically;
- don't do too much color shifting when relighting (e.g.: using neon lights).

This workflow hasn't been tested specifically for other applications, such as product relighting, but I don't see why it can't be integrated with my product relighting workflows.

Import the original image here.
Change sizes as needed.

1.5 models only.

I like prompting only for the light, some other people like prompting everything.

I don't see much difference between the two approaches at very low CFG.
Optional controlNet group, it's set to depth but you can swap it to any other mode by changing the model and the preprocessor.

You can either draw a mask here to use as a light map for relighting, or ->

Drawing is not automated (on the first queue prompt, you'll get an error because you don't have a mask to encode.

<- or you can import a custom mask here.

Custom mask is automated (every single relit will have the same light mask).

Good ol' relighting group.

I like keeping a super low CFG in order to get less changes in the relit image.
This is the blur_size input for the color match nodes. I find it works well when it's at 0, anything more than 0 and it changes the whole workflow.

These four groups ->
on the right are four different ways to color match. I included all of them to give you a choice.
From top to bottom:
- a very simple color matching option, where the relit image's LF layer gets color matched with the original image's LF layer, and it's the worst option (it's useful to see the limitations of such a simple approach to the issue);
- a method using the average of the relit and the original image's LF layers (simple and effective);
- a method using the average of the remapped and color matched LF layers plus the original image (sometimes it works best);
- a method using the resulting average from #3, then averaged out with the relit image as well (closest to the relit image).

Some of these have Image Blending Mode nodes to refine hue and color. Tinker with them to taste.

Each of these groups have a Blur node because I'm an idiot and I can't figure out why there's a bit of oversharpening when recombining the HF and LF layers, so I blur the HF layer by 1 pixel to account for that, bruteforcing a "solution".

The two bottom groups have a a remap node to fix the Blacks and Whites tone range.

Pick one, and you're set!


Cheers!
Andrea

Optional FaceID mask for reconstructing the original face on top of the relit / color matched image. 
I personally don't like how it changes details even at a very low denoise (0.15), but if you don't care about it, you can use this.

Plug the relit / color matched image here.
Plug the original image in the IPAdapter FaceID node.
